						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Disch wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">tomaitheous wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Why couldn't [] have been used instead? There's not mistaking [] for (), and you have () free for preprocessing. LDA [(label+5)*2],y and such.</div><br /><br />Because () is the established standard (read pretty much any 65xx doc in existence, they all use parenthesis)<br /><br />And [] is the established standard for something else (long indirection).</div>
<br /> But if ASM6 is for 6502, what does it matter what [] is used for on other processors. 6502 has no long indirection. Also, would it not be fairly easy to accept both [] and () syntax for addressing in the assembler? I.e. [] encountered implicitly implies short ZP indirect addressing. Or is [] reserved for something else in the assembler?
<br />
<br /> Or maybe a better idea would be to just use <em>lda (&lt;label),y</em> as forced ZP indirect indexed? (sorry if I got the "&lt;" in the wrong direction. I use PCEAS to assemble NES code. Different syntax system. So I don't remember all the other syntax rules).</div>

