				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tomaitheous wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">But if ASM6 is for 6502, what does it matter what [] is used for on other processors. 6502 has no long indirection. Also, would it not be fairly easy to accept both [] and () syntax for addressing in the assembler? I.e. [] encountered implicitly implies short ZP indirect addressing. Or is [] reserved for something else in the assembler?</div><br /><br />I can tell you if I see brackets (e.g. []) used in a "6502 assembler", I'm IMMEDIATELY going to start digging through docs / forums looking to see if the assembler actually supports 65816 and that whoever wrote said code was doing it wrong.  The only characters that I've never seen used in a 65xxx assembler for actual opcode designation are braces (e.g. {}), but that's neither here nor there.<br /><br />The point here that's been partially lost in the chaos is that <strong>there is no</strong> lda (abs),y mode on the 6502.  If a label or equate expands to a 16-bit value (see original example code that started this thread), the assembler should throw an error.  Really.  :-)<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">tomaitheous wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Or maybe a better idea would be to just use <em>lda (&lt;label),y</em> as forced ZP indirect indexed? (sorry if I got the "&lt;" in the wrong direction. I use PCEAS to assemble NES code. Different syntax system. So I don't remember all the other syntax rules).</div>
<br />
<br />"lda (&lt;label),y" also will confuse the person viewing the source; same reason why blargg's "0+(label),y" syntax isn't something I would advocate using unless every use of such contained an inline comment explaining why it's there.
<br />
<br />If I saw "lda (&lt;label),y" I'd immediately say "Why is this forcing use of the low byte of the label/address?  There is no lda (abs),y on the 6502.  Indirect indexed is ZP only!"  Followed by hours spent trying to figure out if there IS a reason they're forcing the low byte of the label/address (e.g. somewhere else in the code using the high byte).
<br />
<br />loopy's already signed off on addressing the issue (pun intended), so there's really not much else to discuss as I see it.  Folks should be familiar with whatever assembler it is they're using -- and use listing generation to debug/verify behaviour of code or the assembler itself.  At least that's how we did it in the "old days".</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

