			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I think the main problem is that in other processors' assembly syntax, a 16-bit operand without parentheses is used to denote a value rather than an address, which is pretty common on the z80 for example, which allows the loading of a register pair with one 16-bit operand.  
<br />
<br />But on the 6502, using direct addressing is the rule rather than the exception, and there is no mode that uses a 16-bit operand as anything but a direct address (with the exception of the indirect address mode JMP also supports).  So the norm became to treat operands as addresses unless otherwise specified, rather than as values.  Parentheses became useful to denote indirect addressing, and 8-bit operands had to be handled similarly to the 16-bit ones to avoid confusion.  And of course with the obvious addition of using a 8-bit operand as a value, they had to use something to denote that, and...well, the hash mark.
<br />
<br />Now I consider myself somewhat adaptable, and in fact am quite capable of adjusting to the assembly syntax of other processors.  But I really don't see the point of changing what has already been in place for the 6502 just to make it more congruent with the assembly syntax of other processors.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Be whatever the situation demands.</div>
					<br clear="all" /><br />

